data.value: Dogs pant primarily as a means of regulating their body temperature. Unlike humans, dogs don't have sweat glands distributed throughout their bodies, except for their paw pads, so panting is their primary method of cooling down. When a dog pants, moisture evaporates from their tongue and the lining of their respiratory tract, dissipating heat and helping to lower their body temperature. Additionally, panting can occur in response to other stimuli, such as excitement, stress, or exertion. In these situations, panting serves as a way for dogs to regulate their breathing and oxygen intake. While panting is a normal and essential physiological response, excessive panting, especially when accompanied by other symptoms like lethargy or drooling, could indicate overheating, dehydration, or an underlying health issue, requiring prompt attention from a veterinarian.
